{"title_page": "Clarence (American TV series)", "text_new": "{{About|the 2014 animated television series|the 1988 television series|Clarence (British TV series)||Clarence (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name=Clarence\n| image=Clarence (2014) logotype.svg\n| image_size=200px\n| genre=[[Comedy]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.amazon.com/Clarence-Season-1/dp/B00JAOCNRK |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-01-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190123185402/https://www.amazon.com/Clarence-Season-1/dp/B00JAOCNRK |archive-date=2019-01-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref><br />[[Slice of life]]\n| creator=[[Skyler Page]]\n| voices={{unbulleted list|Skyler Page {{small|(2014\u201315)}}|Spencer Rothbell {{small|(2015\u201318)}}|[[Sean Giambrone]]|[[Tom Kenny]]|[[Roger Craig Smith]]|[[Katie Crown]]|[[Eric Edelstein]]|[[John DiMaggio]]}}\n| creative_director= Nelson Boles {{small|(2014\u201315)}}<br />David Ochs {{small|(2015)}}\n| director={{unbulleted list|Martin Ansolabehere {{small|(art)}}|[[Andrew Overtoom]] & Helen Roh {{small|(animation)}}|[[Raymie Muzquiz]] {{small|(supervising, Season 1)}}|David Ochs & [[Niki Yang]] {{small|(supervising, Seasons 2\u20133)}}|Vitaliy Strokous & Julia Vickerman<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/juliavickerman/|title=Julia Vickerman (@juliavickerman) \u2022 Instagram photos and videos|website=www.instagram.com}}</ref> {{small|(supervising, Season 3)}}}}\n| theme_music_composer=Simon Panrucker\n| opentheme=\"King of the World\"\n| endtheme=\"Good Habits (And Bad)\", {{small|performed by [[Saba Lou]]}}\n| composer=[[James L. Venable]]<br />Simon Panrucker\n| country=United States \n| language=English\n| network=[[Cartoon Network]] \n| executive_producer={{unbulleted list|Skyler Page {{small|(2014\u201315)}}|Curtis Lelash|Jennifer Pelphrey|[[Brian A. Miller]]|[[Rob Sorcher]]}}\n| producer={{unbulleted list|Keith Mack|{{small|'''Supervising producers:'''}}|[[Bob Boyle (animator)|Bob Boyle]] {{small|(Season 1)}}|Yvette Kaplan {{small|(2014)}}|Nelson Boles {{small|(2015\u201316)}}|Stephen P. Neary {{small|(Seasons 2\u20133)}}}}\n| company=[[Cartoon Network Studios]]\n| distributor=[[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| num_seasons=3\n| num_episodes=130\n| list_episodes=List of Clarence episodes\n| runtime=11 minutes \n| picture_format=[[1080i]] [[HDTV]]\n| audio_format= \n| first_aired={{Start date|2014|2|17}}\n| last_aired={{End date|2018|6|24}}\n| related= \n| website=http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/clarence/index.html\n}}\n'''''Clarence''''' is<!-- Do not change \"is\" to \"was\". Per MOS:TV, fiction is always treated in the present, even if a series has ended, so \"is\" is the correct word to use. --> an American animated television series created by [[Skyler Page]] for [[Cartoon Network]]. The series revolves around a young boy named Clarence and his two best friends Jeff and Sumo. \nPage, a former storyboard artist for ''[[Adventure Time]]'' and revisionist for ''[[Secret Mountain Fort Awesome]]'', developed the series at [[Cartoon Network Studios]] as part of their shorts development program in 2012.\n\nThe pilot aired after the 2014 ''[[Hall of Game Awards]]'' show on February 17, 2014. The series officially premiered on April 14, 2014 and was seen by approximately 2.3 million viewers, outperforming shows in its same demographic in the time slot. The series' pilot was nominated for a [[Creative Arts Emmy Award]]. The series completed its run on June 24, 2018.\n\n==Premise==\nThe series focuses on the daily life of Clarence Wendle, a fun-loving and spirited boy, and his best friends: Jeff, who is the more intellectual type, and Sumo, who often uses drastic measures when solving problems.\n\nClarence lives with his divorced mother Mary and her boyfriend Chad in the fictional town of Aberdale, [[Arizona]], located near [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]]. Each episode focuses on the daily-life situations and problems that Clarence and his friends encounter, and their everyday adventures and life experiences as kids.\n\nOther characters include students and faculty at Aberdale Elementary, Clarence's school. Certain episodes focus on the life of supporting characters, like the citizens of Aberdale and  Clarence's classmates.\n\n==Characters==\n\n===Main===\n[[File:Clarence (2014) screenshot.jpg|thumb|left|The main characters, from left to right: Sumo, Jeff, and Clarence|alt=]]\n*Clarence Wendle (voiced by [[Skyler Page]] {{small|(episodes 1\u201332 and 35\u201336)}} and Spencer Rothbell {{small|(episodes 33\u201334 and 37\u2013130)}}) - An overweight, extroverted, optimistic, and wide-eyed 10-year-old boy who wants to bring out the best in everything and everyone. In the pilot episode, he was the \"new kid\" in Aberdale and could not wait to make friends. He is the kind of person who listens to and follows his heart, reacting toward life with unfailing excitement and enthusiasm. A \"[[nice guy]]\" and proud of it, Clarence enjoys helping people and doing good deeds without rewards, often by using unorthodox methods to do so. He can sometimes let his imagination get the better of him, can get a bit too friendly, and has a bad habit of meddling into people's personal lives. Clarence has a wide range of interests and hobbies, and despite sometimes coming off as a goofball, he more often than not displays an underlying intelligence.\n*{{anchor|Jeff Randell}}Jeffrey \"Jeff\" Randell (voiced by [[Sean Giambrone]]) - Clarence's second best friend. Jeff is by far the most intelligent, levelheaded, and morally inclined of the trio and tries his best to prevent Clarence from going down a bad road. Jeff's most well-known trait is that he has a cube-shaped head which represents his \"square\" personality. He is an avid fan of [[game shows]] and enjoys playing along with them.\n*Ryan \"Sumo\" Sumouski (voiced by [[Tom Kenny]] in the TV series and [[Jason Marsden]] in the pilot) - Clarence's best friend, who is fearless, unpredictable, and often takes drastic and crude measures when trying to solve problems. Despite this often being a drawback, Sumo is loyal to Jeff and Clarence and available when they need support. He and Jeff tend to quarrel with each other due to their opposing personalities, but Clarence acts as the glue that holds the boys' friendships together. In the third season, Sumo was transferred to the new school called West Aberdale.\n\n===Supporting===\n*Mary Wendle (voiced by [[Katie Crown]]) \u2013 Clarence's mother who is always there to support her son no matter the difficulty. She lives with her boyfriend Chad and her son Clarence. It is revealed In \"Hurricane Dilliss\" she has an overbearing mother (now deceased) which makes her very annoyed by her taking over her life.\n*Charles \"Chad\" Caswell III (voiced by [[Eric Edelstein]]) \u2013 Mary's boyfriend who works at various odd-jobs and acts as Clarence's father figure (Although Clarence mostly calls him Chad). Also has a fondness for guitar playing and rock music.\n*Belson Noles (voiced by [[Jason Marsden]] in the pilot episode and [[Roger Craig Smith]] in the TV series) \u2013 The resident bully, who is more likely to use insults and quips rather than use physical violence. Self-absorbed, apathetic, and superficial, Belson is rather unpopular among his peers, yet Clarence is the only one that actually likes him, though the same can't be said for him. Belson is also prone to [[envy]], as he is aggravated by the fact that Clarence is the \"popular kid\" at Aberdale Elementary School and has occasionally tried to ruin his reputation. He is also named after Nelson Boles, who helped create the series. He likely takes after his father, who appears in \"Company Man\" because they both show a desire for complete control over others (the father over his employees, to Belson over the students).\n*Chelsea Keezheekoni (voiced by Grace Kaufman) \u2013 A plucky and outspoken girl who insists that she is superior to any boy, mainly Sumo. She and Sumo have shared a kiss in Clarence, Jeff and Sumo's treehouse in \"Too Gross For Comfort\".\n*Breehn (voiced by [[Joshua Rush]]) \u2013 One of the intelligent kids in class who is more of Jeff's friend than Clarence's, and keeps himself well grounded at all times. However, in later episodes he warms up to Clarence and joins him on some of his misadventures. He becomes a better friend of Clarence, and lets loose when with him.\n*Ms. Melanie Baker (voiced by Katie Crown) \u2013 The children's 4th grade teacher at Aberdale Elementary School who is shown to be helpful and caring, yet easily overwhelmed.\n*Percy Dahmer (voiced by Roger Craig Smith) \u2013 A short, wimpy boy who speaks in a weak voice and is friends with Clarence and Belson.\n*Nathan (voiced by Skyler Page and Damien Haas) \u2013 One of Belson's friends. He's a big guy who is considered dim-witted. He becomes friends with Clarence as well, often participating in his escapades.\n*Dustin Conway (voiced by Kyle Arem) \u2013 Another one of Clarence's classmates and Belson's friends. He later becomes friends with Clarence.\n*Mel Sumouski (voiced by [[John DiMaggio]]) \u2013 Sumo's father who has a stern voice but is really quite wacky.\n*EJ and Sue Randell (voiced by [[Lea DeLaria]] and [[Tig Notaro]]) \u2013 Jeff's [[lesbian]] mothers; EJ has a very similar appearance to Jeff (possibly his birth mother) and has a masculine dress taste, while Sue is free spirited and always shows a patient personality with her son.\n*Jim Reese (voiced by Skyler Page and [[Donovan Patton]]) \u2013 The gruff yet dim-witted vice-principal of the school. He is a former police officer with a voracious appetite.\n*Guyler - A blond-haired boy with a long neck and a big nose. Although generally silent, he does make occasional grunts. He is friends with Clarence, and joins him on his escapades. At first a minor character, he becomes more prominent in later episodes; specifically in \"A Nightmare on Aberdale Street: Balance's Revenge\".\n*Regis Gilben \u2013 A silent and motionless boy who communicates with an eerie wind sound instead of a voice. Everyone can seemingly understand this; also, somehow he is ghost-like and can touch without moving.\n*Mavis (voiced by Spencer Rothbell) \u2013 A squat, red-haired girl who speaks in unintelligible grunts and has a fear of fire hydrants.\n*Joshua \"Josh\" Maverick (voiced by Brent Popolizio) \u2013 A grumpy teenager who doesn't like children, especially Sumo, and later Clarence. He is shown to be very accident prone and constantly gets severe injuries during every one of his appearances.\n*Kimby (voiced by Isabella Niems) \u2013 Another of Clarence's classmates. Kimby is shown as an introverted, awkward, insecure, yet lovely girl who constantly plays with her hair. As a [[girly girl]], Kimby often collects dolls and stuffed animals, enjoys giving and receiving makeovers, and listens to [[boy bands]].\n*Malessica (voiced by Ivy Bishop) \u2013 One of Kimby's friends who is the object of Jeff's affection.\n*Courtlin (voiced by Tayler Buck) \u2013 Another of Kimby's friends. She has a confident personality and isn't afraid to speak her mind.\n*Branda Shoop (voiced by Katie Crown) \u2013 The inattentive, irresponsible guidance counsellor who cares less about the students and more about the rules, safety and herself. She has been working at the school for 29 years, as revealed in \"The Substitute\".\n\n===Others===\n*Amy Gillis (voiced by [[Ava Acres]]) \u2014 A nice girl who is a good friend to Clarence. However, she never appears after her debut in the second episode, \"Pretty Great Day With a Girl\", due to her moving away, save for a cameo in \"Rough Riders Elementary\" and a flashback in \"Clarence For President\".\n*Amy Shutzger (voiced by Skyler Page and Damien Haas) \u2014 A big girl who, along with Mavis, is the only recurring female character to be voiced by a man. She wears her hair in a ponytail and is taller than most of her classmates. She has a crush on Jeff.\n*Blaide (voiced by Skyler Page, Spencer Rothbell, and Grace Kaufman) \u2014 An exchange student.\n*Lauren (voiced by Rachel Eggleston) \u2014 An extremely smart girl who has been homeschooled since she was 6 years old and doesn't know much about the outside world.\n*Cynthia Noles (voiced by [[Mena Suvari]]) \u2014 Belson's mother who doesn't stand up to anyone and doesn't notice her son's mean behavior. She resembles him down to their noses.\n*Mr. Mozer (voiced by [[Carlos Alazraqui]]) \u2014 Sumo's teacher at West Aberdale Elementary who shares a lot with Ms. Baker.\n*Ms. Lofton (voiced by Jenelle Lynn Randall) \u2014 The principal of West Aberdale Elementary.\n*Rosie Randell (voiced by June Squibb) \u2014 EJ's mother and Jeff's grandmother.\n*Mr. and Mrs. Dahmer (voiced by Roger Craig Smith) \u2014 Percy's parents.\n*Walt and Tiffany (voiced by [[Dave Wittenberg]] and Abigail Revasch) \u2014 Breehn's parents.\n\n==Production==\nAt their 2013 upfront, ''Clarence'' was announced along with various other series.<ref name=\"Anderson et. al 2013\" />\nThe series was created by Page, a former storyboard artist for ''[[Adventure Time]]'' and revisionist for ''[[Secret Mountain Fort Awesome]]''.<ref name=\"Milligan 2012\" />\nHe is the fourth creator on the network who graduated from the [[California Institute of the Arts]],<ref name=\"Amidi 2012\" /> and at age 24, he is also the youngest.<ref name=\"Rusak 2014\" />\nAs part of their shorts development program in 2012, the series was developed at [[Cartoon Network Studios]]; four others, ''[[Steven Universe]]'', ''[[Over the Garden Wall (miniseries)|Over the Garden Wall]]'', ''[[We Bare Bears]]'' and ''[[Long Live the Royals]]'' also came from this initiative.<ref name=\"Andreeva 2012\" />\n\nPage, together with creative director Nelson Boles, conceived the series at CalArts. It was further considered when Page became hired at Cartoon Network Studios. A crew of two or three polished the pilot episode; after it had been picked up, a crew of 30 to 35 writers, storyboard artists, revisionists, colorists and designers were employed. Meanwhile, animation is outsourced to South Korea through the [[Saerom Animation]].<ref name=\"Milligan 2014a\" />{{rp|20}} Page explained that the hardest part of production was keeping pace, especially where once an episode is completed, one must start over. He called this \"exciting\", but \"very challenging\".<ref name=\"Milligan 2014a\" />{{rp|21}}\n\nAccording to writer Spencer Rothbell, the series was created with a naturalistic tone, similar to cartoons of the 1990s, combined with a more modern feeling. Given this naturalism, writers can reference works that have inspired for them or fit the genre of an episode. He ultimately felt that it was about \"empowering kids and having fun\".<ref name=\"Serrao 2014\" /> Rothbell also avoids \"pigeonholing\" into one type of story, and that while some plots are mostly character-driven, others are \"based on one idea that we think is really funny\".<ref name=\"Cartoon Network 2014b\" /> Inspiration also came from the shows Page watched as a child, which invoked more poignant and relatable situations. Despite this, elements of fantasy are allowed, and that conveying both incongruous to one another was one technique he particularly enjoyed. Boles noted that the [[art director|art direction]] called for inconsistent character design to avoid having to fit model sheet with the universe perfectly\u2014a result of what he dubs ''the ''[[The Simpsons|Simpsons]]'' effect''.<ref name=\"Milligan 2014a\" />{{rp|20}} Attention is also paid to background characters in order to expand variety in its plot and [[Fictional universe|universe]].<ref name=\"Milligan 2014a\" />{{rp|20\u201321}}\n<!--\n  -- Per policy ([[WP:BLPCRIME]]), mentions of the allegations raised against Page cannot be included until a successful conviction against him has been secured and reported by reliable sources.\n  --\n  -- Please see the following discussion:\n  -- http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Biographies_of_living_persons/Noticeboard/Archive203#Skylor_Page_at_Clarence_.282014_TV_series.29.E2.80.8E\n  \u2013\n  \u2013 See also:\n  \u2013 http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Biographies_of_living_persons#Persons_accused_of_crime\n  -->\n\n===Crossover===\nClarence, Jeff, Sumo, and Belson appeared in \"The Grampies\", the short accompanying the ''[[Uncle Grandpa]]'' episode \"Pizza Eve\", along with other Cartoon Network characters from currently running and ended cartoons. Belson had a speaking role in that short.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jm3DB-mfEuo|title=Cartoon Network Shows Cameo on Uncle Grandpa|first=|last=Mordecai626 Alt|date=16 April 2016|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn the ''[[The Amazing World of Gumball|Amazing World of Gumball]]'' episode \"The Boredom\", Clarence and Mary make an appearance, alongside ''[[Uncle Grandpa]]'' and ''[[Regular Show]]'' characters.\n\nIn the end of the ''[[Steven Universe]]''/''Uncle Grandpa'' crossover episode, \"[[Say Uncle (Steven Universe)|Say Uncle]]\", UG looks over the list of characters from former and current Cartoon Network shows and saw Clarence is the last on his list.\n\n===Page's firing===\nIn July 2014, Skyler Page was fired from Cartoon Network Studios due to cases of sexual harassment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/cartoon-network-fires-creator-of-cartoon-networks-clarence-amid-assault-allegations-1201257951/|title=Cartoon Network Fires Creator of \u2018Clarence\u2019 Amid Sexual Assault Allegations|first=Variety|last=Staff|date=3 July 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2014/07/clarence-skyler-page-cartoon-network-fired-sexual-assault-allegations-emily-partridge-799524/|title=\u2018Clarence\u2019 Creator-Star Out At Cartoon Network Following Sexual Assault Allegations|first=Jen|last=Yamato|date=3 July 2014|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/kateaurthur/clarence-creator-fired#.phD2pwVe3|title=The Creator Of \"Clarence\" On Cartoon Network Has Been Fired After Allegations Of Sexual Assault|publisher=}}</ref> A Cartoon Network spokesperson confirmed that the series would continue despite his absence.<ref name=\"Aurthur 2014\" /> Spencer Rothbell later became head of story and the voice of Clarence.<ref name=\"Milligan 2014b\" />\n\n===Showrunners===\nAfter Page was fired from the series, Nelson Boles, who was previously the series creative director, served as series showrunner for the remainder of the first season. Stephen P. Neary, one of the storyboard artists for the series, took over as showrunner for the second season and onward after Boles left the series early in the second season.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20161118100947/http://www.beyondthecartoons.com/spencer-rothbell/]</ref>\n\n==Cancellation==\nOn April 4, 2017, Spencer Rothbell confirmed that the series' third season would be its last as Cartoon Network did not renew the series for a fourth season,<ref>{{cite web|author=Rothbell, Spencer|date=April 4, 2017|url=https://twitter.com/srothbell/status/849338582850560001|title=got the go ahead so just to confirm - It\u2019s a wrap for Clarence but don\u2019t worry, new episodes will continue to air through 2018|accessdate=April 4, 2017}}</ref> which ended on June 24, 2018.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Main|List of Clarence episodes}}\n{{:List of Clarence episodes}}\n\n==Broadcast and reception==\n<!-- To edit the content in this section you need to edit the \"List of Uncle Grandpa episodes\" page. -->\n''Clarence'' was originally previewed at the 2013 [[San Diego Comic-Con International]].<ref name=\"Wolfe 2013\" />\nCartoon Network had commissioned twelve quarter-hour episodes, with the pilot episode airing after the ''[[Hall of Game Awards]]'' show on February 17, 2014.<ref name=\"Andreeva 2012\" />\nThe pilot was nominated for an \"[[Primetime Emmy Award for Short-format Animation|Outstanding Short-format Animated Program]]\" at the [[65th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]] in 2013.<ref name=\"Television Academy 2013\" />{{efn|Page, [[Peter Browngardt]], [[Robert Alvarez]], [[Brian A. Miller]], Jennifer Pelphrey, Curtis Lelash and [[Rob Sorcher]] were the recipients.<ref name=\"Television Academy 2013\" />}}\nThe first episode, broadcast April 14, 2014, was met with an estimated 2.3 million viewers, outperforming shows in its same demographic in the time slot by double and triple digit percentages.\nMeanwhile, preliminary data identified it as the most watched series premiere for the network that year.<ref name=\"Bibel 2014\" />\n\nIn Canada, ''Clarence'' premiered on [[Cartoon Network (Canada)|Cartoon Network]] on April 14<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CartoonCAN/status/452204316804128768|title=There's a new kid coming to @CartoonCAN & he's SUPER EXCITED to be your friend! Meet #Clarence April 14 at 8pm ET/PT!|work=Twitter|date=April 4, 2015|author=Cartoon Network Canada|accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref> and on [[Teletoon]] on September 4, but it was later moved exclusively to Cartoon Network.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.corusent.com/home/Corporate/PressReleases/tabid/1697/Default.aspx?Id=2785|title=Gotta Gotta See It: TELETOON Launches 2014 Fall Slate|date=August 27, 2014|accessdate=November 17, 2014|publisher=[[Corus Entertainment]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.teletoon.com/en/faq|title=FAQ|work=Teletoon|accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref> The series premiered on October 6 on [[Cartoon Network (Australia and New Zealand)|Cartoon Network]] in Australia and New Zealand<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://pressroom.turner.com/hk/cartoon-network/cartoon-network-toon-machine-lets-aussie-kids-take-control-mum-dad#.VeXdZ_lViko|title=CARTOON NETWORK TOON MACHINE COMING TO AUSTRALIA|date=August 21, 2014|work=Turner Pressroom|publisher=Turner Broadcasting System Asia-Pacific|location=Melbourne|accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eckfactor.com/eck/news/see-the-world-through-the-eyes-of-clarence-a-boy-excited-by-life/|title=See the world through the eyes of Clarence, a boy excited by life|work=Eckfactor|accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref> and on November 3 on [[Cartoon Network (UK & Ireland)|Cartoon Network]] in the United Kingdom and Ireland.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.turnermediainnovations.com/everyones-new-best-friend-is-coming-to-cartoon-network/|title=Everyone's new best friend is coming to Cartoon Network!|date=October 8, 2014|work=Turner Media Innovations|publisher=Turner Broadcasting System Europe|accessdate=September 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612163747/http://www.turnermediainnovations.com/everyones-new-best-friend-is-coming-to-cartoon-network/|archive-date=June 12, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> In India, the series debuted on June 1, 2015 on [[Cartoon Network (India)|Cartoon Network]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/trade-news/hindi/Cartoon-Network-launches-new-show-Clarence/articleshow/47442464.cms|title=Cartoon Network launches new show 'Clarence'|work=The Times of India|date=May 27, 2015|accessdate=September 1, 2015}}</ref> The last 13 episodes of the series aired first in Germany before airing in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fernsehserien.de/clarence/episodenguide|title=Clarence Staffel 3 Episodenguide|work=Fernsehserien|accessdate=April 24, 2019|language=de}}</ref>\n\nIn a three-star review, Emily Ashby of [[Common Sense Media]] alerted parents of \"a similar brand of absurdity and crudeness\" as ''Adventure Time''\u2014though less severe\u2014but praised the cast as \"oddly likable\".<ref name=\"Ashby 2014\" />\nNancy Basile of [[About.com]] applauded the dialogue for its lengthiness, and considered the relationships between the characters to be dynamic and genuine, with some comedy thrown in.<ref name=\"Basile 2014\" /> [[Whitney Matheson]] of ''[[USA Today]]'' found ''Clarence'' to blend optimism and surreal humor in \"just the right amount\", and encouraged children and parents alike to watch its premiere.<ref name=\"Matheson 2014\" />\nIn ''[[Animation Magazine]]'', Mercedes Milligan described it as \"a breath of fresh suburban air\" and a celebration of childhood.<ref name=\"Milligan 2014a\" />{{rp|20}}\nNivea Serrao of ''[[TV Guide]]'' contrasted the show with most fantasy animated series.<ref name=\"Serrao 2014\" />\nBrian Lowry of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' called it \"so quirky and idiosyncratic as to feel fresh\", although it sometimes tread in \"well-worn territory\", but found the character designs unattractive.<ref name=\"Lowry 2014\" />\n\nThe series gained considerable press after featuring a gay couple in the episode \"Neighborhood Grill\", with coverage in various tabloid and entertainment news sites,{{efn|Coverage in these sites include the ''[[Daily Mail]]'',<ref name=\"McCormack 2014\" /> ''[[E! Online]]'',<ref name=\"Harrison 2014\" /> ''[[El Universal (Caracas)|El Universal]]'',<ref name=\"El Universal 2014\" /> [[the Huffington Post|the ''Huffington Post'']] (both in their UK<ref name=\"Bagwell 2014\" /> and US editions<ref name=\"Nichols 2014\" />), ''[[MTV News]]''<ref name=\"Bobb 2014\" /> and ''[[Refinery29]]''.<ref name=\"Barna 2014\" />}} and in [[LGBT]]-oriented sites as well.{{efn|Coverage in these sites include ''[[Pink News]]'',<ref name=\"Day 2014\" />  ''[[Gay Star News]]''<ref name=\"Morgan 2014\" /> and ''[[Queerty]]''.<ref name=\"Tracer 2014\" />}}\nThe scene involves two male characters greeting each other with kisses on the cheek while at a restaurant.\nRothbell originally had the couple kiss on the lips after receiving flowers from the other, but this went unapproved by the network.\nHe added that the scene was a \"minor throwaway moment\", albeit \"better than nothing\", and anticipated that \"one day the main character can be gay and it won't be a big deal\".<ref name=\"Bagwell 2014\" />\nJoe Morgan of ''[[Gay Star News]]'' called the buildup to the scene \"an old joke\",<ref name=\"Morgan 2014\" /> a notion shared by Dan Tracer of ''[[Queerty]]'', although he praised their portrayal \"just as normal people\".<ref name=\"Tracer 2014\" />\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominee\n! Result\n|-\n| 2013\n| [[65th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards|Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Short-format Animation|Outstanding Short-Format Animated Program]]\n| \"Clarence\" (Pilot)\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[British Academy Children's Awards]]\n| International\n| ''Clarence''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2016\n| [[43rd Annie Awards|Annie Awards]]\n| Best Animated TV/Broadcast Production For Children's Audience\n| \"Turtle Hats\"\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==Home media==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=2|Title !! Season(s) !! Episode count !! Running time<br />(minutes) !! Release dates<br />({{USA}}) !! Episodes\n|-\n| style=\"background:#be2128| || ''Cartoon Network Holiday Collection'' || rowspan=3|1 || 1 || 11 || {{Start date|2014|10|7}} || 3\n|-\n| style=\"background:#c3ecf2| || ''Mystery Pi\u00f1ata''<ref name=\"amazon.com\">[https://www.amazon.com/Cartoon-Network-Clarence-Mystery-Pi\u00f1ata/dp/B00OQRUAJ4/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1428456301&sr=8-2&keywords=clarence] {{dead link|date=June 2018}}</ref> || rowspan=2|12\n| rowspan=2|132 || {{Start date|2015|2|10}} || Pilot, 1\u20132, 4\u20135, 7, 11\u201312, 15\u201316, 18, 21, 23\n|-\n| style=\"background:#92d4ea| || ''Dust Buddies''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amazon.com/Clarence-Dust-Buddies-Skyler-Page/dp/B00WUI3KAM/ref=sr_1_4?s=movies-tv&ie=UTF8&qid=1434206039&sr=1-4&K|title=Cartoon Network: Clarence - Dust Buddies V2|date=15 September 2015|publisher=|via=Amazon}}</ref>  || {{Start date|2015|9|15}} || 3, 6, 8, 10, 14, 17, 19\u201320, 25\u20132